      "id": 1,
      "text": "In the 1960s, Michigan businessman Harold Schwartz began selling land in the area now known as The Villages through mail‑order sales.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        23
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Villages%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "A 1968 federal law banning mail‑order real‑estate sales forced Schwartz and partner Al Tarrson to halt that practice.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        24
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Villages%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "By the early 1970s, Schwartz and Tarrson opened Orange Blossom Gardens, a mobile‑home park in northwestern Lake County.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        25
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Villages%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "By the early 1990s, The Villages had grown to over 8,000 residents, three golf courses, and a Winn‑Dixie supermarket.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        29
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Villages%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Between 2010 and 2019, The Villages was the top‑selling master‑planned community in the United States, moving 24,440 homes.",
